ness open to a utopian future. Woven into Cazdyn's analysis are personal anecdotes about his battle with leukemia and his struggle to obtain Canadian citizenship during his illness. These narratives help to illustrate his systemic critique, one that reconfigures the relationship between politics, capitalism, revolution, and the body.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxHealth aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 0aGlobalizationxHealth aspects. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395232zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395232.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles